<dl id="un2040b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un2" href="#un2040">UN2: </a>  <a href="../../ff/unbs/un2all.htm#un2040b"> (VI.D.7) 40(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> la loi des isthmes <small>Not cancelled</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">With high winds constantly blowing in one direction, the rounding of many promontories may be, for a small sailing ship, a sheer impossibility for days, or even weeks, at a time. Hence it was often worth while to land goods on the lee-side of an isthmus, and send them overland either to their destination or to a harbour on the other side, where they could be reshipped and carried #<font color="green">[C2]</font>#<font color="green">[A3]</font>arther. &hellip; Without denying the importance of the &lsquo;<mark>loi des isthmes</mark>&rsquo; in certain cases, it must be pointed out that Troy does not in any sense stand upon an isthmus. <small> Walter Leaf, <a name="WLAS" href="/udra/udex.htm#wlas"><cite title="source">Troy: A Study in Homeric Geography</cite></a> (1912), 257-259</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Copied to <a name="s13006e" href="s13all.htm#s13006e">Sheet 13.006(e)</a>  <br>Raphael transcription: <a name="c16267c" href="../../../f/ff/fnbs/c16all.htm#c16267c">VI.C.16:267(c)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
